<br>
All loot schemes have flaws and bonuses, lots of people (including me) abhor DKP.  God loot I can handle on select items, or if someone requests a raid and does the ground work to make it happen specifically for an item.  I really am just amazed that a guild would let something someone could use rot.  If nothing else don't allow anyone who was at the raid and refused to spend points be allowed to random for it later.  Damn, there are so many other options than letting something good, or even decent, rot, it's just absurd. <p><!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=247362"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:aqua;font-family:Dauphin ;font-size:small;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Bonlainy Trueheart WALKERS<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Epic Crusader, Vazaelle</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yamile>yamile</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Yamdown™</span><br>  Posts: 66<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/13/03 12:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4142.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Loot Rules</span><hr size=1> The random method attempts to create a system where every raid member is equal.  The problem with this system is that people who have not put the time in might get more loot (granted not on purpose, rather by luck) then those that contribute more to the cause and that people that may not need a item as much gain these items over someone else more needy.  This is not a long-term solution because loot distribution is done by a raid-by-raid basis and doesn’t take any long term or guild goals into account.  Granted that if you are at an event you have the same chance as any other participant at gaining an item and that is &quot;fair&quot;.  This is a very good method for those raid less often and have a large possible raid force.  <br>
<br>
God loot works as long as there is trust, and there are enough loots to go around to keep people happy, but in the long term loot questions/divisions will crop up between people.  You will always have issues where a person (or group of persons) is tasked with assigning loots, favoritism is going to be commonplace.  This will always help the guild as a whole progress the fastest, but at the cost of some dissention.   <br>
<br>
Overall I believe that DKP/Point systems are the best method for distributing loots.  For any guild/organization that has events on a regular basis, DKP/Point systems are clearly the best method. There is no more &quot;fair&quot; method then DKP/Point system.  It rewards those who participate and eliminates the 2 big problems of Random and God systems.  They both create division, no matter how tight your guild mates are and how much you trust them, it will create divisions in the long run, it is just human nature, DKP/Point systems eliminate this.   <br>
<br>
The negatives to DKP/Point systems....You have no ability for loot preferences. Your MA isn't necessarily going to be the getting the best gear all the time.  This is realistically the only real negative to DKP/Point systems.  There are some methods to limit the &quot;damage&quot; done by this by having certain clauses that effect loot (ex. Taunt weapons go to Tanks first) but it is one of the main problems with this system.  <br>
<br>
The other and way over blown is the rotting.  This is a big misperception about DKP/Point systems, that things rot all the time.  Yes is does happen but people have to realize why it happens, it happens when people are unwilling to spend point on an item, aka that item is not that big of an upgrade.  Good DKP/Point systems can avoid this from happening by having methods to avoid it (auctions, bidding, reducing prices, twinks, etc.....).  In all the time I have been in a points system (all my EQ time) I have never seen a piece of loot rot that made no sense for it to, every time something has rotted it has been because people just couldn't use it.  <br>
<br>
Realistically all 3 of the systems work and all work better under different conditions. Best thing to do is look at what type of events you will be having, who will be participating, and what type of guild you have and decide what system works the best, then tweak the system to avoid the negatives of that system.  <br>
