<br>
Monk 1 - 90 DKP<br>
Monk 2 - 40 DKP<br>
Rogue 1 - 100 DKP<br>
<br>
Haste moccasins drop off Emperor Ssra.  Monk 1 is using a Runebranded Girdle.  Monk 2 is using a Cloak of Flames.  Rogue 1 is using an Earring of Endless Speed off Doomshade but wants to get the boots and upgrade his earring.<br>
<br>
In this instance, if all 3 asked for it, I'd immediately eliminate monk 2.  I'd give the boots to Monk 1 even though he has less DKP, because he'd get much more use out of it than the rogue, and it would benefit the guild more.  <br>
<br>
Nobody knows the items of every person on a raid, so you can't expect them to know when it's probably not a good idea to request an item.  Rogue 1 probably has no idea that Monk 1 is using the RBG, so he's going to ask for the boots because they're an upgrade for him in his boot slots, and allow him to upgrade his earring for a few more hps.  <br>
<br>
In the end the God system has been considerably more popular for endgame oriented guilds, although there's a number of them out there that do survive on DKP and even flourish with it.  <br>
 <br>
The problem with the God system is that when attendance isn't monitored, sometimes a person who raids 2/3 of what another does is getting just as much loot.  For example, if your guild hands Joe a loot every other week, on average, and he plays every day, then how is it fair to him that Bob also gets a loot every other week, on average, when Bob plays every other day?   <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#FFFFFF>- </font><a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter>Vazaelle.com Community Center</a><font color=#FFFFFF> - </font><a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1>General Discussion</a> <font color=#FFFFFF> - </font><a href="http://www.vazaelle.com">Vazaelle.com</a><font color=#FFFFFF> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.245d<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

